":"Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Buckle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: metonymic occupational name for a maker of buckles or a nickname given to someone who wore a distinctive buckle, from Middle English <i>bokel</i> ‘buckle’.","English: habitational name from either Buckwell in Ashburnham (Sussex) or Buckwell in Kent.","Americanized form of German   Buckel  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Buckels","meanings":["English: variant of   Buckle  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","German: patronymic from   Buckel   1."]},{"name":"Buckles","meanings":["English (Suffolk): variant of   Buckle  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Buckler","meanings":["English: occupational name for a maker of buckles, Middle English <i>bokeler</i>, Old French <i>bouclier</i> (see   Buckle  ). Perhaps in some instances a nickname for a fencer, from Middle English <i>bokeler-player</i>.","German: variant of   Buchler   2.","Americanized form of German <b>Büchler</b> (see   Buechler  )."]},{"name":"Buckel","meanings":["German: from a pet form of the personal name   Burkhart  .","German: descriptive nickname for a person with a hunchback.","German: possibly also a metonymic occupational name for a metalworker, from Middle High German <i>buckel</i> ‘(embossed) buckle on a shield’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Buckle was born in 1502. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Robert Buckle."},"et":{"1502–":"1502–Surnud","1502–Female":"1502–Surnud","1522–Female":"1522–Surnud","1502–Male":"1502–Surnud","1502":"1502","1522":"1522","Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England":"Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England"},"fi":{"1502–":"1502–Kuollut","1502–Female":"1502–Kuollut","1522–Female":"1522–Kuollut","1502–Male":"1502–Kuollut","1502":"1502","1522":"1522","Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England":"Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England"},"fr":{"1502–":"1502–Décédé","1502–Female":"1502–Décédée","1522–Female":"1522–Décédée","1502–Male":"1502–Décédé","1502":"1502","1522":"1522","Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England":"Kelvedon Manor, Essex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Buckle est né en 1502. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Mrs. Robert Buckle."},"de":{"1502–":"1502–Verstorben","1502–Female":"1502–Verstorben","1522–Female":"1522–Verstorben","1502–Male":"1502–Verstorben","1502":"1502","1522":"1522","Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England":"Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England","lifeSummary":"Robert Buckle wurde 1502 geboren. Er hatte mit Mrs. Robert Buckle mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"1502–":"1502–Desede","1502–Female":"1502–Desede","1522–Female":"1522–Desede","1502–Male":"1502–Desede","1502":"1502","1522":"1522","Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England":"Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England"},"hu":{"1502–":"1502–elhunyt","1502–Female":"1502–elhunyt","1522–Female":"1522–elhunyt","1502–Male":"1502–elhunyt","1502":"1502","1522":"1522","Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England":"Kelvedon Manor, Essex, England"},"id":{"1502–":"1502–Telah 